Yes, trees can burn. Trees, like any organic matter, can be combustible and are therefore capable of catching fire under certain conditions. Forest fires, for example, can be caused by lightning strikes or human activities and can result in the burning of trees and other vegetation. The severity of the fire depends on factors such as temperature, humidity, wind, and the type of tree and its moisture content. While some trees may be more fire-resistant than others, all trees can potentially burn under extreme conditions